# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: alice-s-huang
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] He graduated in 1937 with a B.S. from the University of Idaho.
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] At the University of Wisconsin–Madison, he graduated in 1940 with an M.S. and in 1941 with a Ph.D. in medical bacteriology.
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] He received his M.D. in 1944 from the University of Wisconsin School of Medicine and Public Health, where he was a research associate from 1941 to 1942 and an instructor from 1942 to 1943.
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] From 1944 to 1948 he served as an officer in the United States Army Medical Corps.
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] From 1947 to 1948 in Washington, D.C., he was the chief of the chemotherapy research section of the department of viral and rickettsial diseases at the Army Medical Center (which in 1953 was renamed the Walter Reed Army Institute of Research).
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] From 1948 to 1952 at the University of Wisconsin School of Medicine and Public Health, Rasmussen was an associate professor and then a full professor of medical microbiology and preventive medicine.
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] At the UCLA School of Medicine (now named the David Geffen School of Medicine at UCLA), he was appointed in 1952 a full professor in the Department of infectious diseases (which became the department of microbiology and immunology) and chief of the department's virology section.
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] He chaired the department from 1962 to 1969.
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] In 1953 he was appointed to the staff of the City of Hope Cancer Research Institute.
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] In 1969 at the UCLA School of Medicine, he was appointed associate dean, a position he held until his sudden, unexpected death in 1984 from an acute pulmonary embolism.
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] Rasmussen's 1957 paper *Increased susceptibility to herpes simplex in mice subjected to avoidance-Learning stress or restraint*, coauthored by James T.
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] Brill, and his 1969 paper *Emotion and immunity* have foundational roles in psychoneuroimmunology.
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] In the late 1950s and throughout the 1960s, Rasmussen and his colleagues investigated the effects of emotional stress in animal models for various viral infections, such as herpes simplex, Coxsackie B, vesicular stomatitis, poliomyelitis, and polyoma.
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] For the academic year 1960–1961, he was on sabbatical as a visiting scientist at the United States Naval Research Unit 2 in Tapei.
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] During his sabbatical year he found that the influenza virus that caused the 1957–1958 influenza pandemic was closely related to at least 4 different influenza viruses occurring in Asia among pigs, ducks, chickens, and horses.
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] Rasmussen was elected in 1953 a fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] He was the president of the American Society for Microbiology for the academic year 1972–1973.
[src:alice-s-huang/aaron-frederick-rasmussen-jr] Their son, Frederick Tatum Rasmussen (1943–2020), became a lawyer and partner at several law firms in Seattle.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] Abigail Salyers was born in Louisville, Kentucky and attended high school in Arlington, Virginia at Wakefield High School.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] During high school, she was at risk of expulsion due to being pregnant, but she graduated in 1959 and with the help of her English teacher, Mrs.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] Salyers went on to receive her undergraduate degree in Mathematics in 1963 and a Ph.D. in Nuclear Physics in 1969 from George Washington University, Washington, D.C.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] Four years into her first academic position teaching and researching physics at St.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] Mary's College, Salyers chose to switch her focus to microbiology as a post-doctoral researcher at Virginia Polytech Institute.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] She began to study the metabolism of the anaerobic microbes of the human intestinal tract, particularly the anaerobic bacterium *Bacteroidetes*.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] In 1978, Salyers started her own lab at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] There she met her long-time life partner and fellow professor Jeffrey Gardner, as well as her research associate and collaborator Nadja Shoemaker.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] In 1983, she became the first woman professor in the Microbiology Department to be granted tenure, and in 1988 was promoted to full professor.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] William Arends Professor in Molecular and Cellular Biology.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] As a lecturer at the University of Illinois, Salyers worked tirelessly to revitalize the inaccessible medical school curriculum.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] In her teaching, she emphasized the importance of microbiology as the defining biological discipline of the coming decades and its relevance to her students.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] To accompany her work in the classroom, she co-authored the textbook *Bacterial Pathogenesis: A Molecular Approach* with Dixie Whitt, with whom later collaborations followed.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] As a result of her educational efforts, Salyers was invited to be Co-Director of the Microbial Diversity Summer Course at the Marine Biological Laboratory in Woods Hole, MA for the summers of 1995–1999.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] Salyers’ microbiome research was based in the study of the physiology of the anaerobic bacterium *Bacteroides*, with particular regard to their carbohydrate metabolism and their ability to harbor mobile antibiotic resistance genes.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] Her lab at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign developed genetic tools that helped to expanded on her earlier research on polysaccharide transport and fermentation in *Bacteroidetes*.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] These tools fueled the discovery of the processes though which the bacterium sequesters complex carbohydrates inside the cell and anaerobically degrades them.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] In the human colon, these metabolic processes result in important byproducts which are utilized by other gut microflora and by the human host.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] In developing these genetic tools, Salyers’ lab discovered conjugative transposons, a type of mobile genetic element which can transfer genes for antibiotic resistance among gut bacteria.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] Initially, they used transposons as markers for genetic analysis.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] But Salyers also realized that transposons could carry antibiotic resistance genes between microbial cells in the human gut.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] They investigated the tightly regulated molecular mechanisms of the horizontal transfer of these mobile antibiotic resistance genes and discovered that *Bacteroides* acted as a reservoir of these genes in the human colon.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] The many tools that Salyers developed to work with her “funny bugs” and the discoveries she made are responsible for the prominence of *Bacteroidetes* as a model organism in microbiology today.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] In 2001, Salyers was named President of the 40,000 member American Society for Microbiology.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] Her tenure overlapped with the 2001 anthrax attacks when she advised the US Postal service about the safety precautions.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] She learned that providing basic information to the postal workers about the bacterium made it possible to have discussions about sophisticated topics in microbiology in a simple way, and that having that information made them feel less frightened.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] In 2005, Salyers co-signed an open letter to the director of the NIH that asked the NIH to continue to fund research that had the capacity to broadly improve public health, instead of narrowly focusing on biodefense funding.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] She was also one of the first to recognize the public health risks of antibiotic resistant bacteria, and to convey the growing issue to the public.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] This included co-authoring *Revenge of the Microbes: How Bacterial Resistance is Undermining the Antibiotic Miracle* (again with Dixie Whitt), which summarized the latest information on bacterial pathogenesis and antibiotic resistance for a broad audience.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] Salyers was also president of the board for El Centro, a center that provided help for local Latino migrant workers in Illinois.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] She published over 220 scientific articles.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] Salyer has also provided her expert testimony regarding genetically modified plants and antibiotic use in agriculture to several regulatory agencies in the U.S. and Europe.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] In 2014 after her death, the Salyers Symposium was held at the University of Illinois at Urbana-Champaign to commemorate her life and work.
[src:alice-s-huang/abigail-a-salyers] She was cited as the inspiration for the book *Women in Microbiology*.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] Born in Cornwall-on-Hudson, New York, he grew up in Northampton, Massachusetts.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] His father was a professor of physics at Smith College.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] Alan also became a physicist, doing his undergraduate and doctoral work at Princeton University from which he obtained his Ph.D. in 1916.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] He joined the faculty of the University of Cincinnati, and married Vassar graduate Mary Mallon (sister of Henry Neil Mallon) there in August 1917.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] He later became a professor at Yale University, and moved to North Haven, Connecticut in 1929.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] During World War II, he took leave of absence from Yale to become director of field operations for the Office of Scientific Research and Development and the family moved to Cambridge, MA.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] He continued his government work and became deputy chief of the Office of Naval Research.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] In 1950, he was appointed by President Truman as first director of the U.S.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] National Science Foundation (NSF) Waterman was awarded the Public Welfare Medal from the National Academy of Sciences in 1960.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] He served as director until 1963, when he retired and was subsequently awarded the Presidential Medal of Freedom.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] Alan and Mary had six children: Alan Jr, an atmospheric physicist who taught at Stanford University, Neil, Barbara, Anne, and Guy, writer, climber, and conservationist.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] Possessed of a gentle nature, Alan Waterman was known for his calm and reasoned point of view.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] Besides his scientific talents, he was an accomplished musician, revealing his sense of humor by walking the corridors of the National Science Foundation playing his bagpipes.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] He had a fine voice and singing together was a family ritual.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman canoed the rivers and lakes of northern Maine during extensive summer trips in the 1930s and 1940s.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] He was accompanied by his sons and colleagues, in particular Karl Compton, then president of MIT.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman was known to say that becoming a licensed Maine Guide meant possibly more to him than his NSF appointment.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] In 1961, he was chosen as one of 50 outstanding Americans of meritorious performance in the fields of endeavor, to be honored as a Guest of Honor to the first annual Banquet of the Golden Plate in Monterey, California.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] Honor was awarded by vote of the National Panel of Distinguished Americans of the Academy of Achievement.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] The crater Waterman on the Moon is named after him, as is Mount Waterman in the Hughes Range of Antarctica.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] Since 1975, the National Science Foundation has annually issued the Alan T.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] Waterman Award (named in Waterman's honor) to a promising young researcher.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] A month later after his death, President Lyndon B.
[src:alice-s-huang/alan-tower-waterman] Johnson made a statement to commemorate him.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Albert Abraham Michelson was born on December 19, 1852, in Strelno (now Strzelno, Poland), Prussia, into a Polish-Jewish family.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] He moved to the United States with his parents in 1855, at the age of 2.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] He grew up in the mining towns of Murphy's Camp, California, and Virginia City, Nevada, where his father was a merchant.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] His family was non-religious, and Michelson himself was a lifelong agnostic.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] He spent his high school years in San Francisco in the home of his aunt, Henriette Levy (née Michelson), who was the mother of author Harriet Lane Levy.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] His sister was the novelist Miriam Michelson.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Grant awarded Michelson a special appointment to the U.S.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] During his four years as a midshipman at the Academy, he excelled in optics, heat, climatology and technical drawing.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] After graduating in 1873 and two years at sea, he returned to the Naval Academy in 1875 to become an instructor in physics and chemistry until 1879, when he was posted to the Nautical Almanac Office, Washington (part of the United States Naval Observatory) to work with Simon Newcomb.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] The following year, he took a leave of absence to continue his studies in Europe; he visited the universities of Berlin and Heidelberg in Germany, and the Collège de France and École polytechnique in Paris, France.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated with the sciences, in particular the problem of measuring the speed of light.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] While in Annapolis, he conducted his first experiments on the speed of light as part of a class demonstration in 1877.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] His Annapolis experiment was refined, and in 1879, he measured the speed of light in air to be 299864±51 kilometres per second, and estimated the speed of light in vacuum as 299940 km/s, or 186380 mi/s.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] After two years of studies in Europe, he resigned from the Navy in 1881.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In 1883, he was appointed Professor of Physics at the Case School of Applied Science in Cleveland, Ohio, and concentrated on developing an improved interferometer.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he and Edward Morley carried out the famous Michelson–Morley experiment, which failed to detect evidence of the existence of the luminiferous ether.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] He later moved on to use astronomical interferometers in the measurement of stellar diameters and in measuring the separations of binary stars.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In 1890, Michelson became a professor at Clark University in Worcester, Massachusetts.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In 1892, he was appointed Professor and the first head of the Department of Physics at the newly-organized University of Chicago, where he remained until his retirement in 1929.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Michelson returned to military service in the closing months of World War I as a Lieutenant Commander in the Naval Reserve, serving in the Bureau of Ordnance.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] He was promoted to Commander in the reserve in May 1919 and was recalled briefly to active duty in the 9th Naval District before being released from service on September 30, 1921.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died on May 9, 1931, in Pasadena, California, at the age of 78.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was fascinated by light all his life.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Once asked why he studied light, he reputedly said, "because it's so much fun".
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] As early as 1869, while serving as an officer in the United States Navy, Michelson started planning a repeat of the rotating-mirror method of Léon Foucault for measuring the speed of light, using improved optics and a longer baseline.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] He conducted some preliminary measurements using largely improvised equipment in 1878, about the same time that his work came to the attention of Simon Newcomb, director of the Nautical Almanac Office who was already advanced in planning his own study.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's formal experiments took place in June and July 1879.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] He constructed a frame building along the north sea wall of the Naval Academy to house the machinery.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Michelson published his result of 299,910 ± 50 km/s in 1879 before joining Newcomb in Washington DC to assist with his measurements there.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Thus began a long professional collaboration and friendship between the two.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Simon Newcomb, with his more adequately funded project, obtained a value of 299,860 ± 30 km/s, just at the extreme edge of consistency with Michelson's.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Michelson continued to "refine" his method and in 1883 published a measurement of 299,853 ± 60 km/s, rather closer to that of his mentor.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In 1906, a novel electrical method was used by E.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Rosa and the National Bureau of Standards to obtain a value for the speed of light of 299,781 ± 10 km/s.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Though this result has subsequently been shown to be severely biased by the poor electrical standards in use at the time, it seems to have set a fashion for rather lower measured values.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] From 1920, Michelson started planning a definitive measurement from the Mount Wilson Observatory, using a baseline to Lookout Mountain, a prominent bump on the south ridge of Mount San Antonio ("Old Baldy"), some 22 miles distant.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In 1922, the United States Coast and Geodetic Survey began two years of painstaking measurement of the baseline using the recently available invar tapes.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] With the baseline length established in 1924, measurements were carried out over the next two years to obtain the published value of 299,796 ± 4 km/s.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Famous as the measurement is, it was beset by problems, not least of which was the haze created by the smoke from forest fires which blurred the mirror image.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] The now-famous Michelson–Morley experiment also influenced the affirmation attempts of peer Albert Einstein's theory of general relativity and special relativity, using similar optical instrumentation.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] These instruments and related collaborations included the participation of fellow physicists Dayton Miller, Hendrik Lorentz, and Robert Shankland.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] The period after 1927 marked the advent of new measurements of the speed of light using novel electro-optic devices, all substantially lower than Michelson's 1926 value.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Michelson sought another measurement, but this time in an evacuated tube to avoid difficulties in interpreting the image owing to atmospheric effects.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In 1929, he began a collaboration with Francis G.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Pease and Fred Pearson to perform a measurement in a 1.6 km tube 3 feet in diameter at the Irvine Ranch near Santa Ana, California.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In multiple reflections the light path was increased to 5 miles.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] For the first time in history the speed of light was measured in an almost perfect vacuum of 0.5 mm of mercury.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Michelson died with only 36 of the 233 measurement series completed and the experiment was subsequently beset by geological instability and condensation problems before the result of 299774±11 km/s, consistent with the prevailing electro-optic values, was published posthumously in 1935.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] During June and early July 1879, Michelson refined experimental arrangements from those developed by Hippolyte Fizeau and Léon Foucault.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] For instance, he adopted a steel measuring tape with a said length of 100 feet and he intended to measure tens of times across the distance; still, he measured its length against a copy of the official standard yard to find out it as 100.006 feet, thus eliminating a systematic error, albeit small.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Aside from the efforts to reduce as much as possible the systematic errors, repeated measurements were performed at multiple levels to obtain more accurate results.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] To realize that, he also strived to have each measurement not influencing each other, thus being mutually independent random variables.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] A statistical model for repeated measurements with the assumption of independence or identical distributions is unrealistic.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In the case of light speed study, each measurement is approached as the sum of quantity of interest and measurement error.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] The law of large numbers suggests to estimate the expectation by the sample mean.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In 1887, he collaborated with colleague Edward Williams Morley of Western Reserve University, now part of Case Western Reserve University, in the Michelson–Morley experiment.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Their experiment for the expected motion of the Earth relative to the aether, the hypothetical medium in which light was supposed to travel, resulted in a null result.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Surprised, Michelson repeated the experiment with greater and greater precision over the next years, but continued to find no ability to measure the aether.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] The Michelson–Morley results were immensely influential in the physics community, leading Hendrik Lorentz to devise his now-famous Lorentz contraction equations as a means of explaining the null result.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] There has been some historical controversy over whether Albert Einstein was aware of the Michelson–Morley results when he developed his theory of special relativity, which pronounced the aether to be "superfluous".
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In a later interview, Einstein said of the Michelson–Morley experiment, "I was not conscious it had influenced me directly ...
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] I guess I just took it for granted that it was true." Regardless of Einstein's specific knowledge, the experiment is today considered the canonical experiment in regards to showing the lack of a detectable aether.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] The precision of their equipment allowed Michelson and Morley to be the first to get precise values for the fine structure in the atomic spectral lines for which in 1916 Arnold Sommerfeld gave a theoretical explanation, introducing the fine-structure constant.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Pease made the first measurement of the diameter of a star other than the Sun.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Michelson had invented astronomical interferometry and built such an instrument at the Mount Wilson Observatory which was used to measure the diameter of the red giant Betelgeuse.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] A periscope arrangement was used to direct light from two subpupils, separated by up to 20 feet (6m), into the main pupil of the 100 inch (2.5m) Hooker Telescope, producing interference fringes observed through the eyepiece.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] The measurement of stellar diameters and the separations of binary stars took up an increasing amount of Michelson's life after this.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Beginning in the 1970s, astronomical interferometry was revived, with the configurations using two (or more) separate apertures (with diameters small compared to their separation) being often referred to as "Michelson Stellar Interferometry".
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] This was to distinguish it from speckle interferometry, but should not be confused with the Michelson interferometer which is one common *laboratory* interferometer configuration of which the interferometer used in the Michelson–Morley experiment was an instance.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Michelson's concept of interfering light from two relatively small apertures separated by a substantial distance (but with that distance, or *baseline*, now often as long as hundreds of meters) is employed at modern operational observatories such as VLTI, CHARA and the U.S.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Gravitational waves are detected using a Michelson interferometer with a laser light source.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In 2020 there were three Michelson interferometer gravitational wave detectors operational, and a fourth under construction.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] These Michelson interferometers have arms 4 kilometers in length, set at 90 degree angles to each other, with the light passing through 1 m diameter vacuum tubes running their entire length.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] A passing gravitational wave will slightly stretch one arm as it shortens the other.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] This is precisely the motion to which these Michelson interferometers are most sensitive.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] As of 2020 fifteen gravitational wave events had been observed using these Michelson interferometers.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In the 1890s Michelson built a mechanical device called the harmonic analyzer, for computing coefficients of Fourier series and drawing graphs of their partial sums.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Stratton published a paper about this machine in the *American Journal of Science* in 1898.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In 1877, Michelson married Margaret Hemingway, daughter of a wealthy New York stockbroker and lawyer and the niece of his commander William T.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In 1899, Michelson married Edna Stanton.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] He is a great uncle of physicist Peter Michelson.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In Season 3 Episode 26 of the television series *Bonanza* ("Look to the Stars", broadcast March 18, 1962), Ben Cartwright (Lorne Greene) helps the 16-year-old Michelson (portrayed by 25-year-old Douglas Lambert (1936–1986)) obtain an appointment to the U.S.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Naval Academy, despite the opposition of the bigoted town schoolteacher (played by William Schallert).
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] *Bonanza* was set in and around Virginia City, Nevada, where Michelson lived with his parents prior to leaving for the Naval Academy.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In a voice-over at the end of the episode, Greene mentions Michelson's 1907 Nobel Prize.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] The home in which Michelson lived as a child in Murphys Camp, California, was in the store of his father, first on Main Street, across from the Sperry & Perry Hotel, and after the 1859 fire in a store next to the hotel.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] His aunt Bertha Meyers owned a house on Main Street toward the east end of town and Michelson probably visited her family there frequently.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] New Beast Theater Works in collaboration with High Concept Laboratories produced a 'semi-opera' about Michelson, his obsessive working style and its effect on his family life.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] The production ran from February 11 to 26, 2011, in Chicago at The Building Stage.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Michelson was portrayed by Jon Stutzman.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] The play was directed by David Maral with music composed by Joshua Dumas.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Norman Fitzroy Maclean wrote an essay "Billiards Is a Good Game"; published in *The Norman Maclean Reader* (ed.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Alan Weltzien, 2008), it is an appreciation of Michelson from Maclean's vantage point as a graduate student regularly watching him play billiards.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] The University of Chicago Residence Halls remembered Michelson and his achievements by dedicating 'Michelson House' in his honor.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Case Western Reserve has dedicated a Michelson House to him, and Michelson Hall (an academic building of science classrooms, laboratories and offices) at the United States Naval Academy also bears his name.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Laboratory at Naval Air Weapons Station China Lake in Ridgecrest, California, is named for him.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] There is a display in the publicly accessible area of the Lab which includes facsimiles of Michelson's Nobel Prize medal, the prize document, and examples of his diffraction gratings.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] In 2017, a newly renovated physics research center at the University of Chicago was renamed in honor of Michelson as well.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Numerous awards, lectures, and honors have been created in Albert A.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award presented every year by the Computer Measurement Group; the Albert A.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] Michelson Award given by the Navy League of the United States; and the Michelson Memorial Lecture Series presented annually by the Division of Mathematics and Science at the U.S.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-a-michelson] The Computer Measurement Group gives the annual A.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] He had a brother and two sisters and his parents were Jewish immigrants to the United States from Russia.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] Albert Balows grew up in Colorado Springs, Colorado and graduated from Palmer High School.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] He graduated in 1942 with a B.A. in biology from Colorado College.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] From 1943 to 1946 he served in the United States Army Medical Corps and participated in the 1944–1945 military campaign of Patton's 3rd Army.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] Balows graduated in 1948 with an M.S. in microbiology from Syracuse University and in 1952 with a Ph.D. in microbiology from the University of Kentucky.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] At the University of Kentucky, his mentor was Ralph Holder Weaver (1903–1973).
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] From 1952 to 1969 Balows worked as a clinical microbiologist at the Saint Joseph Hospital in Lexington, Kentucky.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] He supervised both the hospital's clinical microbiology and the transfusion medicine services.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] In 1960 he was appointed an associate professor of medicine at the University of Kentucky Medical Center, where he taught, directed the center's clinical microbiology laboratory, and established a research program.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] In 1969 he moved to the Atlanta area to join the staff of the Centers for Disease Control (CDC).
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] He worked as the CDC's director of the bacteriology division from 1969 to 1981 and then as the CDC's assistant director of laboratory science from 1981 to 1988, when he retired.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] He worked with the World Health Organization and travelled the globe in connection with his career.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] Balows was from 1974 to 1979 editor-in-chief of the *Journal of Clinical Microbiology* and served on the editorial boards of 12 journals.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] He did research on AIDS, toxic shock syndrome, Legionnaires' disease, Ebola virus, group B streptococci, *Histoplasma capsulatum*, and other problems in public health.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] He was the author of more than 95 book chapters and the author or coauthor of numerous article in scientific journals.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] He and his colleagues planned countermeasures against, and provided surveillance for, possible bioterrorist activity at the 1984 Summer Olympics, and helped to evaluate the safety of the White House's water supply and how to safeguard it against bioterrorism.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] Balows was elected in 1971 a fellow of the American Association for the Advancement of Science.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-balows] In October 1956 he married Patricia Ann Barker (1932–2017).
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Professor Prescott was born on December 12, 1832, in Hasting, New York.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was the youngest of four children in Benjamin Prescott and Experience Huntley Prescott’s household.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] His ancestor John Prescott migrated from England to Boston in 1640.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] William Hickling Prescott, the prominent historian, and Colonel William Prescott, the commander in the battle of Bunker Hill, were also of the same lineage as Albert Prescott.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] With so many influential figures in his family, Prescott undoubtedly showed a desire to succeed at an early age.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Unfortunately, at the age of nine, he suffered a critical injury to his right knee from a major fall that crippled him for life.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] His mother’s opposition to amputate the leg prevented further complication but the injury made his stay indoor for about five years.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] That was the “seed-time of his future.” During those years, he developed an interest in literature and writing.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] He read a vast collection of books from the district circulating library at his home and wrote short reviews and storied on them.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Under the guidance of his sister and private tutors, he gained knowledge of Latin, French, German and various branches of science.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] His father, Benjamin Prescott, died in 1848 leaving his oldest son in charge of the household.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Sixteen-year-old Prescott decided to join his older brother to work on the farm for next three years while continuing his education.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] At that time, he joined the anti-slavery protest by becoming a correspondent of a paper called The Liberator.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further worked as a correspondent for the New York Tribune in 1853.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] While working as a correspondent, he continued his education under private instruction.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] He enjoyed history, literature, and writing but found his true passion for science and analytical works.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] He decided to pursue a career in medicine and began to prepare himself to get into a medical school.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] He taught in the neighborhood school while preparing for admission.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1857, he started to work for a well-known physician named Dr.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Greenleaf was his mentor for three years until he entered the department of Medicine and Surgery at the University of Michigan in 1860, graduating with a degree in Doctor of Medicine in 1864.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott joined the Union Army and was appointed as an Assistant Surgeon in Totten Hospital of Louisville, Kentucky after passing the medical service examination in the United States Army.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Later in the war, he became a member of the Medical Board of Examiners and Chief Surgeon of Foundry Hospital in Louisville.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] A few months later, he was appointed to be the Chief Surgeon of the Jefferson General Hospital in nearby Port Fulton.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1865, he was dismissed from the army with a rank of Brevet Captain.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott took the offer to be an Assistant Professor of Chemistry and Lecturer of Organic Chemistry and Metallurgy at the University of Michigan.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1868, he was in charge of the newly formed School of Pharmacy.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Just two years after that, he was promoted to be a professor of Organic and Applied Chemistry and Pharmacy.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] In 1879, he became the dean of the School of Pharmacy and in 1884, the director of the Chemical Laboratory.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1898.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Revolutionary changes in the curriculum of pharmaceutical education were one of Dr.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Throughout the nineteenth century, a prerequisite for the higher level pharmaceutical study was based mostly on apprenticeship programs where pharmacists learned on a practical basis.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to professor Edward Parrish, member of the Philadelphia College of Pharmacy, the goal of the apprenticeship programs were to give students a pre-professional experience and prepare them for admission to courses offered by colleges.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] However, there were no legal requirements for preparatory training in high school prior to the enrollment in an apprenticeship program.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] So College of Pharmacy continued to enroll students that were experts on memorizing drug names and doing hands-on work but lacked in fundamental knowledge of basic science.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott gained responsibility of the School of Pharmacy in University of Michigan, he took quite an innovative step by launching a program that not only offered extensive laboratory experience in basic science but also eliminated the requirement for apprenticeship for the first time in history.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Many including, the editor of American Journal of Pharmacy, William Procter were skeptical about the merit of the diploma offered at the University due to such non-traditional course requirements.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott was even denied to be a delegate to the American Pharmaceutical Association (APhA) meeting in 1871.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] According to the clause of byLaws of APhA, “All colleges of Pharmacy or local Pharmaceutical Organizations shall be entitled to five representatives” but the University of Michigan did not fall under the definition of School of Pharmacy or Pharmaceutical Organization due to its different curriculum.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott presented his response saying that apprenticeship was not the best way to teach students since it ignored the nature of materials the students deal with.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] He further supported his argument by saying that “the pharmacist that trained the apprentice was also a recipient of a non-scientifically oriented apprenticeship” so there was no net advancement in actual pharmaceutical knowledge.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Besides advocating for laboratory-based pharmaceutical education, he promoted preparatory courses prior to college enrollment.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott’s innovative steps might not have been welcomed at first but eventually, educators and leaders in charge of pharmaceutical education realized the importance of his acts and adapted to the new changes.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Prescott House, located within the East Quadrangle dormitory on the University of Michigan's Central Campus, was named in his honor.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-benjamin-prescott] Additionally, an early student organization associated with the College of Pharmacy was called Prescott Club.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] Albert Francis Blakeslee was born on November 9, 1874, in Geneseo, New York, to Augusta Miranda Hubbard Blakeslee and Francis Durbin Blakeslee, a Methodist minister.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee attended Wesleyan University, graduating in 1896.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Wesleyan, Blakeslee played several sports and won academic prizes in mathematics and chemistry.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] He received a master's degree from Harvard University in 1900 and a doctorate in 1904.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] He also studied at the University of Halle-Wittenberg in Germany from 1904 to 1906.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] After graduating from Wesleyan, Blakeslee taught at the Montpelier Seminary in Vermont, as well as at the East Greenwich Academy.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] His first professorship was at the Connecticut Agricultural College, now known as the University of Connecticut.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was hired by the Carnegie Institution in 1915, eventually becoming its director.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] In 1941, Blakeslee retired from the Carnegie Institution and returned to academia, accepting a professorship at Smith College.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] He would go on to direct the Smith College Genetics Experimentation Station.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] At Smith, he performed his research on jimsonweed.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee used the jimsonweed plant as a model organism for his genetic research.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] His experiments included using colchicine to achieve an increase in the number of chromosomes, which opened up a new field of research, creating artificial polyploids and aneuploids, and studying the phenotypic effects of polyploidy and of individual chromosomes.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee married Margaret Dickson Bridges in 1919.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee died in Northampton, Massachusetts, on November 16, 1954.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] Blakeslee was awarded the Bowdoin Prize for this discovery of sexual fusion in fungi.
[src:alice-s-huang/albert-francis-blakeslee] He was elected to the American Philosophical Society in 1924, the United States National Academy of Sciences in 1929, and the American Academy of Arts and Sciences in 1940.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Huang, was orphaned at age 12 in Anhui, China, and was taken in by a missionary.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] He was later educated at the University of Pennsylvania and the Philadelphia Divinity School, returning to China as an Anglican bishop.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] He later married Huang's mother, Grace Betty Soong.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Huang's mother, Grace Betty Soong, was from Jiangxi Province where her family had large land holdings.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Grace's father appreciated the practical work of Christian missionaries and allowed several of his children to become Christian instead of remaining Buddhist.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Huang was born in Nanchang, the capital city of Jiangxi Province, in 1939.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Mary's Hall-Doane Academy (in Burlington, New Jersey), the National Cathedral School (in Washington, D.C.), and Wellesley College (in Wellesley, Massachusetts).
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Huang received her B.A., M.A., and Ph.D.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] (1966) degrees from Johns Hopkins University.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Huang's research focused on defective interfering particles (DIPs) which can be utilized to combat viruses.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] DIPs are composed of viral structural proteins and sets of DNA or RNA which are incomplete.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] These DIPs will interfere in replication of the virus because they are reproduced at the expense of a standard viral particle.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Huang's work on DIPs has been utilized to combat cancer, HIV, and plant related diseases.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] At Johns Hopkins and MIT her work for Robert R.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Wagner and future husband David Baltimore was "to purify and characterize interfering viral particles".
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] They studied the inhibition of cellular RNA synthesis by nonreplicating vesicular stomatitis virus, known to infect horses, cattle and swine.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] At the time, biologists knew the central dogma to be DNA to RNA to protein, with DNA replication as the way to replicate ones genome.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Huang and Baltimore unraveled that RNA viruses were different and used RNA polymerase to replicate its RNA genome, but they discovered an enzyme, reverse transcriptase (in a mouse leukemia retrovirus), that converts RNA to DNA (involved in a process now known as reverse transcription).
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Baltimore later received the Nobel Prize in 1975 for his discovery.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Huang and Baltimore coauthored a paper with Martha Stampfer titled "Ribonucleic acid synthesis of vesicular stomatitis virus, II.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] An RNA polymerase in the virion." This paper went on to show that “the virions of vesicular stomatitis virus contain an enzyme that catalyzes the incorporation of ribonucleotides into RNA”.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] While at Harvard Medical School, Huang continued to study how mutant strains produced by rabies-like virus interfered with further growth of the viral infection.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] In 1977, she was awarded the Eli Lilly Award in Microbiology and Immunology for this research.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] From 1971 to 1991, Huang taught at Harvard Medical School as a Microbiology and Molecular Genetics professor.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] At Harvard, Huang served as coordinator of the Virology Unit at the Channing Laboratories of Infectious Diseases at Boston Medical Center for two years, and as director of the "Virus-Host Interactions in Cancer" training program (funded by the National Cancer Institute) for fifteen years.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Huang directed the Laboratories of Infectious Diseases at Boston Children's Hospital in 1979, where she studied viral diseases in pediatric patients.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] At New York University, Huang participated in a project in science education and received a grant that focused on improving teachers’ preparation and ability to engage students in science exploration and discovery.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] At New York University, Huang was appointed as dean of science; She took on the role from 1991 to 1997.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Huang is an emeritus member of the board of trustees of the Keck Graduate Institute of Applied Life Sciences (KGI).
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Huang is a former trustee of the Waksman Foundation for Microbiology and a trustee of the Public Agenda.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] She was pointed a council member of the California Council on Science and Technology in 2004 and served for two terms.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] In June 2015, Huang wrote an advice article for the Science Careers website.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] A female postdoctoral scholar asked what she should do in response to her advisor looking down her shirt.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Huang, who was married to her own postdoctoral advisor, replied, "I suggest you put up with it, with good humor if you can." Following strong reaction on social media, the article was removed within hours of being posted.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] After the article was removed, Science Careers tweeted, "We apologize for printing it.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] It does not reflect our values or standards".
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] A fuller apology claimed the article had not "undergone proper editorial review prior to posting." In an interview, Huang stood by her advice, saying, "What I try to do is give advice from experience, and to give the advice that would serve the writer well into the long-term future.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] I’m taking their best interests to heart rather than being in one camp or another camp or trying to push my own political agendas." She said she hoped to write a follow-up column with other people’s suggestions for dealing with the situation.
[src:alice-s-huang/alice-s-huang] Huang was married in 1968 to David Baltimore.
